    "summary": "The Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) was formally founded at the First Summit Conference held in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, in September 1961, bringing together 25 heads of state committed to non-alignment with either of the major Cold War power blocs led by the United States and the Soviet Union. The movement grew out of the spirit of the [[event:2735|Bandung Conference]] of 1955 and was primarily organized by Yugoslav President Josip Broz Tito, Indian Prime Minister Jawaharlal Nehru, Egyptian President Gamal Abdel Nasser, Indonesian President Sukarno, and Ghanaian President Kwame Nkrumah.\n\nThe NAM represented an assertion of political independence by newly decolonized and developing nations, who sought to maintain strategic autonomy without being drawn into the ideological competition and military alliances of the superpowers. Member states committed to principles including anti-imperialism, national sovereignty, and peaceful coexistence. The movement grew substantially over subsequent decades, encompassing most of the world's developing nations.\n\nIn practice, the degree of genuine non-alignment varied considerably among members, with some maintaining close ties to one bloc or the other. The NAM's practical effectiveness as a political force was limited by internal divisions and the economic dependency of many members on the major powers. However, it provided a diplomatic forum for developing nations to coordinate positions in the United Nations and to articulate alternative visions of world order.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-Aligned_Movement",
